{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625833"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17044"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17044"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.12,0.85,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76990"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9734"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17044"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62496"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5291"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23058"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76990"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe mammalian target of rapamycin (mTOR) is a protein kinase that integrates signals from growth factors, nutrients and cellular energy status to regulate cell growth and division.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of mTOR inhibitors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks antibody production by B cells","Prevents complement cascade activation","Increases regulatory T cell production","Inhibits T cell proliferation and differentiation","Suppresses neutrophil degranulation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EmTOR inhibitors primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting T cell proliferation and differentiation\u003C/strong\u003E. They block the mTOR signalling pathway, which is crucial for T cell activation and clonal expansion in response to interleukin-2 and other growth signals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking antibody production by B cells\u003C/strong\u003E may occur indirectly through reduced T cell help, this is not the primary mechanism of action\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreventing complement cascade activation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a function of mTOR inhibitors as they do not interact with the complement system\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing regulatory T cell production\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as mTOR inhibitors actually suppress all T cell proliferation including regulatory T cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppressing neutrophil degranulation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant effect of mTOR inhibitors\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy inhibiting T cell responses, mTOR inhibitors are useful as immunosuppressants in organ transplantation and in treating certain proliferative disorders where the mTOR pathway is overactive.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The mammalian target of rapamycin (mTOR) pathway regulates cell growth, proliferation and survival through protein kinase activity.","mTOR inhibitors suppress T cell proliferation and differentiation, making them useful as immunosuppressants.","Common clinical uses of mTOR inhibitors include preventing organ transplant rejection and treating certain cancers."],"references":["Dowling RJ, Topisirovic I, Fonseca BD, Sonenberg N. Dissecting the role of mTOR: lessons from mTOR inhibitors. Biochim Biophys Acta. 2010;1804(3):433-439. doi:10.1016/j.bbapap.2009.12.001","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62496"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17044"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62496"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:00:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:01:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9734"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76990"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying